    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The issue with your function is that you're incrementing `d` only once per iteration of the outer loop, which can lead to unnecessary iterations for larger inputs. We can optimize this by incrementing `d` twice per iteration. \n\nHere's the optimized function:\n\n```python\ndef find_prime_factors(n):\n    factors = []\n    d = 2\n    temp = n\n    while temp > 1:\n        while temp % d == 0:\n            factors.append(d)\n            temp //= d\n        d += 1\n        d += 1  # Increment d twice per iteration\n    return factors\n```\n\nHowever, this still has a time complexity of O(sqrt(n)) due to the nested loops. We can further optimize it by only incrementing `d` when a factor is not found. Here's the final optimized function:\n\n```python\ndef find_prime_factors(n):\n    factors = []\n    d = 2\n    while d * d <= n:\n        while n % d == 0:\n            factors.append(d)\n            n //= d\n        d += 1\n    if n > 1:\n        factors.append(n)\n    return factors\n```\n\nThis function will pass the runtime",
